{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"## Part 1 — Defect audit\n\n### 1. Register or word-choice faults\n\n- **2:** “**possessed of life**” is an affected substitute for *alive* or *living*; “**the vital functions still going on**” then shifts awkwardly into colloquial phrasing.\n- **5:** “**recoverable at need**” is conspicuously archaic diction for a modern computing sense; *recoverable when needed* is idiomatic.\n- **13:** “**leaves of writing or print**” is a faulty collocation. Leaves may *bear* writing or print; they are not naturally “of writing or print.”\n- **19:** “**soft-footed**” is a literary and imprecise substitute for the relevant anatomical description, such as *having padded paws*.\n- **21:** “**a glad occasion**” is affected, antiquated diction in this context.\n- **30:** “**under grief, pain, or other strong emotion**” uses the wrong collocation. One weeps *from* or *because of* grief or pain, not “under” it.\n- **37:** “**above all one of some note**” is a strained use of *above all*. The required expression is *especially one of some importance*.\n- **41:** “**the flaming state of what burns**” is an unnatural and conceptually muddled circumlocution for combustion or burning.\n- **42:** “**an animal of the water**” is unidiomatic in place of *an aquatic animal*; “**gilled for breathing and finned for swimming**” is mannered, artificially symmetrical diction.\n- **46:** “**apart from kin or romance**” compresses unlike categories into an unnatural construction. Friendship is not properly defined by being “apart from” kinship or romance.\n- **50:** “**mourning over a loss**” substitutes the response to grief for grief itself. *Grief* is deep sorrow; *mourning* is its expression or observance.\n- **59:** “**the arms being clasped about another person in affection**” is stiffly contrived, and “**in affection**” is the wrong collocation; *as an expression of affection* would be natural.\n- **63:** “**to voice mirth or amusement**” is a strained collocation. One *expresses* mirth or *gives voice to* amusement.\n- **82:** “**set down on a flat surface**” is an affected and inaccurate substitute for *represented*, *drawn*, *painted*, or *recorded*. Many pictures are not literally “set down.”\n- **95:** “**that recurring state**” is an oddly deictic opening with no antecedent and sounds like literary exposition rather than a clean definition.\n\n### 2. Vague anaphoric renaming\n\nnone found.\n\nUses of *thing* in entries such as 36, 62, 70, 71, and 98 denote an object being classified, made, or taken; they do not vaguely rename the headword itself.\n\n### 3. Staged observers\n\nnone found.\n\nReferences to “**the eye**” in 27 and 67 describe visual perception as part of the meaning; they do not invent generic onlookers.\n\n### 4. Non-definitional material\n\n- **62:** “**so that it remains of that class for as long as it exists**” is an appended metaphysical claim about the permanence of classification, not part of the meaning of *kind*. It is also not generally true: things can change kind or be reclassified.\n\n## Part 2 — Overall naturalness\n\n**4/10.**\n\nThe collection is intelligible, and some entries are entirely natural—especially **1**, “**filled with fear or apprehension**,” which is the most natural entry. Others that read cleanly include 34, “**a domesticated carnivorous mammal of the wolf family**,” and 91, “**to move on foot at speed, both feet leaving the ground in each stride**.”\n\nAs a set, however, the definitions sound systematically manufactured in an old-fashioned pseudo-lexicographic voice. Telltale formulations include “**possessed of life**” (2), “**a glad occasion**” (21), “**above all one of some note**” (37), “**the flaming state of what burns**” (41), “**gilled for breathing and finned for swimming**” (42), and “**to voice mirth**” (63). The recurrent balanced clauses and literary circumlocutions make the entries feel rewritten to avoid ordinary dictionary wording.\n\nThere are also conspicuous precision problems that professional editing would catch: 23 restricts a child to someone “**below the age of puberty**”; 44 includes “**whatever is eaten or drunk**” as food; 75 equates a mother specifically with “**the woman who has borne a child**”; and 106 calls the water of “**seas**” both “**clear**” and “**tasteless**.”\n\nThe least natural entry is **62**: “**the class to which a thing belongs by its very nature, so that it remains of that class for as long as it exists**.” It reads as improvised philosophical commentary, not as a professionally edited definition."}}
